# This ensures:
  #
  #    ✅ All text files use LF (Unix line endings) in the repository
  #    ✅ Git auto-converts CRLF → LF when committing from Windows
  #    ✅ Scripts work correctly in Linux CI runners

# Run these commands to apply this file:
# git add --renormalize .
# git commit -m "chore: normalize line endings"


# or Git config: git config --global core.autocrlf true
# 👉 Git will automatically:
  # - normalize line endings on commit
  # - prevent inconsistencies
# Avoid it if: You are working in a professional team; you should insist on a .gitattributes file to ensure the
# repo stays clean for everyone

# The best practice for modern development—especially in teams—is to use a
  #.gitattributes file
# While git config --global core.autocrlf true was a standard recommendation for years, it has major drawbacks
# compared to the file-based approach.



# 🔹 Normalize all text files automatically
* text=auto

# 🔹 Enforce LF in repo for source files
*.py text eol=lf
*.md text eol=lf
*.txt text eol=lf
*.yml text eol=lf
*.yaml text eol=lf
*.json text eol=lf

# 🔹 Windows scripts (if any)
*.bat text eol=crlf
*.ps1 text eol=crlf

# 🔹 Binary files (never modify)
*.png binary
*.jpg binary
*.jpeg binary
*.gif binary
*.pdf binary
*.sh     text eol=lf
Dockerfile text eol=lf

